1. Simulation in R (40% of the HW2 grade)

1) Generate stationary AR(p), MA(q) and ARMA(p,q) processes. With \(p,q \leqslant 5\)

Consider an ARMA(p,q) process of a general form:

\[ y_{t} = \beta_1y_{t-1} + \beta_2y_{t-2} + ... + \beta_py_{t-p} + \varepsilon_{t} + \theta_1\varepsilon_{t-1} + ... + \theta_q\varepsilon_{t-q},\ \varepsilon_{t} \sim iddN(0, \sigma^2)\tag{1} \]

In order to reduce code repetitions, create a function that generates ARMA(p,q) processes of any order \(p\) and \(q\).

# helper function to create lagged matrix of y
lag_mat <- function(y, p) {
  if (p == 0) {
    as.matrix(y)
  } else {
    p <- 1:p
    tmp <- lapply(p, function(i) c(rep(NA,i), head(y, length(y)-i)))
    res <- do.call(cbind, tmp)
    colnames(res) <- paste0("L", p)
    res
  }
}

# function to generate arma(p,q) process
my_arma <- function(ar = NULL, ma = NULL, n = 1000, seed = 1, sd = 1) {
  # set initial values
  lag_ar <- if (is.null(ar)) 0 else length(ar) # set the order of ar process
  lag_ma <- if (is.null(ma)) 0 else length(ma) # set the order of ma process
  lag_bigger <- if (lag_ar > lag_ma) lag_ar else lag_ma # equals to the greatest order of p and q
  n <- n + lag_bigger # number of obs + the greatest order
  
  set.seed(seed) # set a seed for reproducibility
  epsilon <- rnorm(n = n, mean = 0, sd = sd) # generate errors
  y <- numeric(n) # set a zero-vector for y
  
  # process generation function
  for (i in ((1+lag_bigger):n)) {
    y[i] <- sum(ar * lag_mat(y, lag_ar)[i,]) + sum(ma * lag_mat(epsilon, lag_ma)[i,]) + epsilon[i]
  }
  y[(1 + lag_bigger):n] # get rid of initial zero values, return ARMA series
}

For example, choose \(p = 2\) and \(q = 2\). Set \(\beta_1 = 0.2\), \(\beta_2 = 0.5\), \(\theta_1 = 0.5\), \(\theta_2 = -0.2\).
For the sake of comparison, coefficient of individual AR an MA processes are chosen to match ones of ARMA process.
Therefore, the task it to simulate processes \((2)-(4)\):

\[ AR(2): y_{t} = 0.2y_{t-1} + 0.5y_{t-2} + \varepsilon_{t} \tag{2} \]

\[ MA(2): y_{t} = \varepsilon_{t} + 0.5\varepsilon_{t-1} -0.2\varepsilon_{t-2} \tag{3} \]

\[ ARMA(2,2): y_{t} = 0.2y_{t-1} + 0.5y_{t-2} + \varepsilon_{t} + 0.5\varepsilon_{t-1} -0.2\varepsilon_{t-2} \tag{4} \]

\[ \varepsilon_{t} \sim iddN(0, 1)\tag{5} \]

Generate series and plot them:

# set parameters
my_ar <- c(0.2, 0.5) # set the order p of ar process
my_ma <- c(0.5, -0.2) # set the order q of ma process
n <- 1000 # number of obs to generate
seed <- 133 # set seed
sd <- 1 # standard deviation of an error term

# generate processes
arma20 <- my_arma(ar = my_ar, n = n, seed = seed, sd = sd) # ar(2)
arma02 <- my_arma(ma = my_ma, n = n, seed = seed, sd = sd) # ma(2)
arma22 <- my_arma(ar = my_ar, ma = my_ma, n = n, seed = seed, sd = sd) # arma(2,2)

# create a plot for AR(2)
p1 <- ggplot(mapping = aes(y = arma20, x = seq(1, n))) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Simulated AR(2) process",
       x = "t",
       y = "*y<sub>t</sub>*") +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_markdown())

# create a plot for MA(2)
p2 <- ggplot(mapping = aes(y = arma02, x = seq(1, n))) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Simulated MA(2) process",
       x = "t",
       y = "*y<sub>t</sub>*") +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_markdown())

# create a plot for ARMA(2,2)
p3 <- ggplot(mapping = aes(y = arma22, x = seq(1, n))) +

  labs(title = "Simulated ARMA(2) process",

Write down estimated equations to double-check for a correctness of generation:

mod20 <- arima(arma20, order = c(2,0,0), include.mean = FALSE)
mod02 <- arima(arma02, order = c(0,0,2), include.mean = FALSE)
mod22 <- arima(arma22, order = c(2,0,2), include.mean = FALSE)

\[ AR(2): \hat{y}_{t} = 0.2290\hat{y}_{t-1} + 0.4570\hat{y}_{t-2} \tag{6} \]

\[ MA(2): \hat{y}_{t} = \hat{\varepsilon}_{t} + 0.5028\hat{\varepsilon}_{t-1} -0.2545\hat{\varepsilon}_{t-2} \tag{7} \]

\[ ARMA(2,2): \hat{y}_{t} = 0.2668\hat{y}_{t-1} + 0.4783\hat{y}_{t-2} + 0.4330\hat{\varepsilon}_{t-1} -0.2857\hat{\varepsilon}_{t-2} \tag{8} \]

As you can see, the coefficients in \((6)-(8)\) are pretty close to ones in \((2)-(4)\).

Prepare the data:

  • Import quarterly.xls data set;
  • Transform a string with dates in into yearquarter format;
  • Convert data frame into a tsibble format;
  • Filter data to match the range used in the Endersâ textbook (1961 Q4 - 2012 Q4 period);
  • Create spread variable by subtracting r5 from Tbill .
df <- read_excel("quarterly.xls")
df <- df %>% mutate(DATE = yearquarter(DATE))
df_tsb <- df %>% as_tsibble(index = DATE)
df_model <- df_tsb %>% filter_index("1961 Q4" ~ "2012 Q4")
df_model <- df_model %>% mutate(spread = r5-Tbill)

Estimate the models.

# estimate the models
arima700 <- arima(df_model$spread, order = c(7,0,0))
arima600 <- arima(df_model$spread, order = c(6,0,0))
arima200 <- arima(df_model$spread, order = c(2,0,0))
wierd_mod1 <- arma(df_model$spread, lag = list(ar = c(1, 2, 7)))
arima101 <- arima(df_model$spread, order = c(1,0,1))
arima201 <- arima(df_model$spread, order = c(2,0,1))
wierd_mod2 <- arma(df_model$spread, lag = list(ar = c(1, 2), ma = c(1,7)))

# create list of models to iterate over them
model_list <- list(arima700, arima600, arima200, wierd_mod1, arima101, arima201, wierd_mod2)

Calculate additional metrics: \(AIC\), \(SBC\), \(SSR\), \(Q(4)\), \(Q(8)\), \(Q(12)\).

n_models <- length(model_list)

# helper function to calculate BIC from AIC
my_bic <- function(model) {
  aic <- summary(model)$aic
  n <- length(df_model$spread)
  p <- if (class(model) == "arma") length(summary(model)$coef[,1]) else length(summary(model)$coef)
  p*log(n) + summary(model)$aic - 2*p
}

# create data frame for metrics
df_metrics <- data.frame("SSR" = rep(0, n_models),
                         "AIC" = rep(0, n_models),
                         "SBC" = rep(0, n_models),
                         "Q4" = rep(0, n_models),
                         "Q8" = rep(0, n_models),
                         "Q12" = rep(0, n_models))

for (i in 1:n_models) {
  df_metrics$SSR[i] <- sum(na.omit(model_list[[i]]$residuals)^2)
  df_metrics$AIC[i] <- summary(model_list[[i]])$aic
  df_metrics$SBC[i] <- my_bic(model_list[[i]])
  df_metrics$Q4[i] <- Box.test(na.omit(model_list[[i]]$residuals),
                                     lag = 4, type = "Ljung")$statistic
  df_metrics$Q8[i] <- Box.test(na.omit(model_list[[i]]$residuals),
                               lag = 8, type = "Ljung")$statistic
  df_metrics$Q12[i] <- Box.test(na.omit(model_list[[i]]$residuals),
                                lag = 12, type = "Ljung")$statistic
}
